s that could indicate the occurrence of torsade de pointes such as dizziness, lightheadedness, fainting, palpitation, irregular heart rhythm, shortness of breath, or syncope.', 'Metabolism, Synergism', NULL, NULL, 'Major', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/155993/', '[1] "Product Information. VFEND (voriconazole)." Pfizer U.S. Pharmaceuticals, New York, NY.[2] Katari SR, Magnone M, Shapiro R, et al "Clinical features of acute reversible tacrolimus (FK 506) nephrotoxicity in kidney transplant recipients." Clin Transplant 11 (1997): 237-42[3] Assan R, Fredj G, Larger E, Feutren G, Bismuth H "FK 506/fluconazole interaction enhances FK 506 nephrotoxicity." Diabete Metab 20 (1994): 49-52[4] Pai MP, Allen S "Voriconazole inhibition of tacrolimus metabolism." Clin Infect Dis 36 (2003): 1089-91[5] Osowski CL, Dix SP, Lin LS, Mullins RE, Geller RB, Wingard JR "Evaluation of the drug interaction between intravenous high-dose fluconazole and cyclosporine or tacrolimus in bone marrow transplant patients." Transplantation 61 (1996): 1268-72[6] Dodds-Ashley E "Management of drug and food interactions with azole antifungal agents in transplant recipients." Pharmacotherapy 30 (2010): 842-54[7] "Product Information. Noxafil (posaconazole)." Schering-Plough Corporation, Kenilworth, NJ.[8] Venkataramanan R, Zang S, Gayowski T, Singh N "Voriconazole inhibition of the metabolism of tacrolimus in a liver transplant recipient and in human liver microsomes." Antimicrob Agents Chemother 46 (2002): 3091-3[9] Mieles L, Venkataramanan R, Yokoyama I, Warty VJ, Starzl TE "Interaction between FK506 and clotrimazole in a liver transplant recipient." Transplantation 52 (1991): 1086-7[10] Manez R, Martin M, Raman V, et al. "Fluconazole therapy in transplant recipients receiving FK506." Transplantation 57 (1994): 1521-3[11] Floren LC, Bekersky I, Benet LZ, et al. "Tacrolimus oral bioavailability doubles with coadministration of ketoconazole." Clin P